SIMULATION FOR EDUCATION ONLY — NOT FOR GUIDING PATIENT CARE
========================================================================

This is not a medical device. It is not validated for clinical use. It
must not be used to guide the care of a real patient.

  1. Confirm everything locally. Every threshold, interval, safety margin
     and procedure in this simulator must be checked against your own
     unit's policy and the manual of the generator you actually use.
     Devices differ. Where this simulator and your local policy disagree,
     YOUR LOCAL POLICY IS RIGHT and this simulator is wrong.

  2. It is an adjunct, not a replacement. It is a teaching aid, and it is
     meant to be used alongside experienced clinical instruction, with a
     supervisor in the room who can correct it. It is not a substitute
     for that instruction, and it is not a substitute for supervised
     practice on the real device.

  3. The device is generic. It is modelled on a typical dual-chamber
     external pulse generator, not on any particular manufacturer's box.
     Control layout, ranges, defaults and indicator behaviour vary. Some
     scenarios depend on features a given generator may or may not have —
     Scenario 10 (cross-talk), for instance, assumes the box has no
     ventricular safety pacing, which many temporary units indeed lack
     but some do not.

  4. The physiology is simplified. It simulates at the level of cardiac
     timing and events, which is the level at which pacemaker behaviour
     operates and the level that matters for teaching. It is not a
     cellular or biophysical model, and the waveform shapes are stylised.

  5. Clinical decisions are not modelled. The simulator can tell you what
     a box does. It cannot tell you what a patient needs.

If you adapt this work, you accept responsibility for the clinical
accuracy of your adaptation, and you must not represent it as validated
for clinical use. Please retain this notice.


